Multifamily Risk Score 
Class A/B/C Apartment Market Analysis USA 
Daksha Gummadi 

1. Problem Statement 
Real estate investors who own or manage multifamily apartment properties need to know where rents are heading. If rents are about to grow they want to invest more. If rents are about to fall they want to reduce exposure or raise rents early. Most investors currently rely on lagging reports that come out months after market changes have already occurred.  The goal of this project is to build a machine learning model that predicts year over year rent growth for US multifamily properties using economic and market indicators that are available before rent changes actually show up in the data. The target variable is rent_growth_yoy which is a continuous number making this a regression problem. 

2. Data Sources 
Three primary data sources were used: 
- Zillow ZORI (Observed Rent Index) covers 544 US metro areas from 2015 to 2025. This is the primary rent data source. Each metro has monthly rent values in dollars. I calculated national average rent and year over year growth from this dataset. 
- FRED Rental Vacancy Rate (RRVRUSQ156N) from the US Census Bureau reports the percentage of rental units that are empty each quarter. Low vacancy means tight supply and supports higher rents. 
- FRED Building Permits (PERMIT) tracks new housing construction permits issued each month in thousands. This is a leading indicator of future supply. 
Three additional economic features were added from FRED: 
- Timber PPI (WPU081) tracks lumber prices. When wood is expensive less new construction happens which supports rents. 
- CPI Inflation (CPIAUCSL) measures the general rate of price increases year over year. High inflation tends to push rents higher. 
- Unemployment Rate (UNRATE) measures labor market health. Low unemployment means more people can afford to rent. 

3. Data Wrangling
The Zillow data came in a wide format with one column per month. I reshaped it to a long format so each row represented one metro area in one month. I then calculated the national average rent across all 544 metros for each month. The vacancy rate data was quarterly so I used linear interpolation to fill in the missing monthly values. The Zillow dates were end of month format while vacancy and permits used start of month format. I converted all dates to the start of the month before merging to make sure  the datasets aligned correctly.  I created property class segments by ranking all metros by rent each month. The top 25 percent became Class A, the middle 50 percent became Class B, and the bottom 25 percent became Class C. Year over year growth rates were calculated for each class and for the national average. Lag features were created for vacancy rate, building permits and rent growth using the previous month values. The final cleaned dataset was saved as master_dataset_cleaned.csv for use in EDA and modeling. 

4. Preprocessing 
A separate preprocessing notebook handled dummy variable encoding and feature standardization. The dataset had no traditional categorical variables requiring dummy encoding. The only object type column was the date column which was dropped since year, month and quarter were already extracted as numeric features.  All numeric features were standardized using StandardScaler so they all have a mean of zero and standard deviation of one. This is important because features like average rent range from around 1,144 to 1,370 while growth rates range from about negative 2 to 14. Without scaling a model might over-weight rent simply because its numbers are larger. The scaler was saved so new data can be transformed consistently. 

5. Exploratory Data Analysis 
The EDA revealed a clear boom and bust cycle in the rental market. Rent growth was around 3 to 4 percent in early 2020 then exploded to 10 to 14 percent during 2021 and 2022 driven by post COVID demand and very low vacancy rates. After peaking in 2022 growth dropped sharply and turned negative by late 2025. 
Key findings: 
- Vacancy rate hit a low of 5.6 percent in 2021 which was the tightest market in years. It climbed back above 7 percent by 2025 which coincided with falling rents. 
- Building permits surged to nearly 1900 thousand units in late 2021 and 2022. Those apartments finished in 2024 and 2025 creating oversupply that pushed vacancy up. 
- Class A peaked highest at about 14.5 percent growth in 2022. Class B peaked around 11.5 percent. Class C had the lowest peak at about 6.8 percent. 
- All three property classes moved together with correlations above 0.95 for rent levels and 0.85 to 0.90 for growth rates confirming they respond to the same market forces.
- Previous month rent growth had a very high correlation with current rent growth making it the strongest predictor in the dataset. 

6. Modeling Approach 
Stationarity Testing:
Before modeling I tested each feature using the Augmented Dickey Fuller test. A stationary series has a consistent mean and variance over time which makes patterns more reliable for prediction. Three features failed the test: vacancy rate, building permits, and inflation. I applied first differencing to those three columns which means subtracting the previous month value from the current month. After differencing all three passed with p-values of 0.0000. 
Sliding Window Augmentation:
The raw dataset had only 55 usable rows after stationarity treatment. With an 80 percent training split that left only about 43 rows for training which is not enough for complex models. I used a 12 month sliding window to augment the data. A window of 12 months slides one month at a time and each position predicts the 13th month. Features for each row are the mean, standard deviation, minimum, and maximum of each variable over the 12 month window. This produced 43 augmented rows with 32 features each. 
Train and Test Split: 
I used a chronological split with the first 80 percent of rows for training and the last 20 percent for testing. No shuffling was applied because this is time series data. Shuffling would allow the model to train on future months and test on past months which would give misleadingly high scores. TimeSeriesSplit with 5 folds was used for cross validation inside the training set so each validation period always came after its training period. 

7. Model Results 
Three models were built and compared using four metrics on the held out test set. R2 measures what fraction of variance the model explained. A negative R2 means the model did worse than just predicting the average every time. MAE is the average prediction error in percentage points. RMSE penalizes large errors more heavily. Train R2 is included to check for overfitting. 
