8. Final Model: Random Forest 
Random Forest was selected as the final model. It was the only model with a positive Test R2 meaning it was the only one that actually learned useful patterns from the data. Linear Regression and Ridge Regression both produced negative Test R2 scores which means they performed worse than just guessing the average every time. This happened because with 32 features and only 43 training rows both linear models overfit severely to the training data and failed on new months. Random Forest handled this better because it builds many trees on random subsets of the data and averages their predictions. This ensemble approach reduced the impact of noise in the small training set. 
