9. Recommendations 
Based on the findings of this project here are three concrete recommendations for multifamily investors and operators. 
Watch building permits as a leading signal. Permits were the most important predictor in the model by a wide margin. When monthly permits start declining from elevated levels it signals that future supply pressure will ease and rent growth may stabilize or recover. Investors should monitor monthly FRED permit data as an early warning indicator. 
Use vacancy rate as a real time risk gauge. When vacancy climbs above 6.5 to 7 percent it is a strong signal that rent growth will slow or turn negative. Operators should consider locking in longer lease terms before vacancy rises to protect revenue stability. 
Consider Class C properties for lower volatility. The EDA showed Class A had the biggest growth swings peaking at 14.5 percent and dropping to negative. Class C was more stable and predictable. Investors seeking consistent returns with less risk should consider shifting some exposure toward affordable housing. 

10. Limitations and Future Work 
Limitations: 
The dataset only covers 2020 to 2025 which includes the unusual COVID period. A longer history would improve model reliability. 
All predictions are at the national average level. Metro level predictions would be more actionable for investors. 
The test set is only 9 months which limits confidence in the test scores. 
Random Forest Test R2 of 0.08 is low. The model is directionally useful but not yet production ready.
Future improvements: 
Add mortgage rate and interest rate data from FRED as additional features.
Expand to metro level modeling using the full Zillow dataset. 
Test gradient boosting models like XGBoost once more historical data is available.
Gather more years of data to grow the training set and improve model performance. 

